State the conclusion from your test, and explain how you arrived to your conclusion. Hint: This part is mostly a review of Homework04 material. So, if youre unsure how to do some of these tasks, I recommend revisiting Homework04 and its solutions.

First, lets compute the sample mean and variance, as well as the corresponding Normal density:

#sample mean and variance for log sulphates
log.mean.est = mean(log(wine$sulphates))
log.var.est = var(log(wine$sulphates))
#defining the Normal density for log sulphates
wine$sulphates.lognormDensity = dnorm(log(wine$sulphates), mean = log.mean.est, sd = sqrt(log.var.est))

Now, here is the desired histogram of log(sulphates) on the density scale, with an overlayed density curve of a Normal distribution:

library(latex2exp)
#Histogram and density curve for log sulphates
ggplot(wine, aes(x = log(sulphates))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), fill = "darkgreen", bins = 35) +
  geom_line(aes(log(sulphates), sulphates.lognormDensity)) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Log(Sulphates Content)",
       x = TeX("Log Sulphates Content (log(\\frac{g}{dm^3}))"),
       y = "Density")

Now well perform KS test to assess if log(sulphates) follows a Normal distribution:

ks.test(x = log(wine$sulphates), y = "pnorm", mean = log.mean.est, sd = sqrt(log.var.est))
## Warning in ks.test(x = log(wine$sulphates), y = "pnorm", mean = log.mean.est, :
## ties should not be present for the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  log(wine$sulphates)
## D = 0.079069, p-value = 4.149e-09
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

We see that the p-value of this KS test is very small, and thus we reject the null hypothesis that log(sulphates) follows a Normal distribution. This makes sense - looking at our above plot, the density does not fit log(sulphates) well. In particular, there appears to be too much mass on the left side of the curve and not enough on the right side, such that the mode of the Normal density curve is to the right of the mode in the data.

  1. (6 points) After seeing the work you did in the previous part, Professor Pablo says, Ive heard that the Shapiro-Wilk test is more powerful than the KS test to detect violations of Normality. So, given what you found in Part A, dont you think you should use the Shapiro-Wilk test instead, since it has more power?

Given your results in Part A, do you think Professor Pablo is bringing up a relevant point here, or do you think what hes saying is irrelevant, given your results? By relevant, I mean, Yes, the Professor Pablo is right - I should have run a test with more statistical power, and it may have given a different conclusion. Meanwhile, by irrelevant, I mean, No, running a test with more statistical power wouldnt change my conclusion. State whether you think Professor Pablos point is Relevant or Irrelevant, and then explain in 1-3 sentences.

Professor Pablo is right that the KS test doesnt have a lot of power, but that isnt an issue here (i.e., this comment is Irrelevant), because, despite this low power, we still rejected the null hypothesis that the data are Normally distributed in Part A. Having low power is only an issue when you fail to reject a null hypothesis, because the rate of Type 2 errors is equal to 1 - power, meaning that low power will result in more occurences of incorrectly failing to reject the null hypothesis. However, that is Irrelevant here, because we rejected the null hypothesis. In general, rejecting the null from a low-powered test should give you a lot of confidence in that rejection, because that must mean that the null hypothesis has to be strongly violated for the low-powered test to detect that violation. In short, Professor Pablo is showing off that he read the Wikipedia page for the Shapiro-Wilk test, but he is inappropriately applying that Wikipedia knowledge here.

  1. (8 points) Professor Pablo thinks the graph you made in the previous part is pretty cool, but technically it does not communicate any formal statistical conclusions. As a follow-up to your graph in Part C, answer the following questions:
  • Does the variance of log(sulphates) differ across different qualities? In your answer, include the code you used to run the appropriate statistical test, state your formal conclusion from this test, and explain how you arrived at your conclusion.

As we discussed in class and lab, Bartletts test allows you to assess if the variance of a quantitative variable is different among different categories. Here is the code to run Bartletts test:

bartlett.test(log(sulphates)~quality, data = wine)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  log(sulphates) by quality
## Bartlett's K-squared = 27.039, df = 5, p-value = 5.604e-05

We see that the p-value is quite small (and certainly less than 0.05); thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the variance of log(sulphates) is the same across all of the quality groups, thereby concluding that they are different.

  • Does the mean of log(sulphates) differ across different qualities? Run an appropriate statistical test to answer this question. Within the function you use to answer this question, specify var.equal = TRUE or var.equal = FALSE based on your conclusion in the first part of this question. In your answer, include the code you used to run the appropriate statistical test, state your formal conclusion from this test, and explain how you arrived at your conclusion.

As we discussed in class and lab, one-way ANOVA allows you to assess if the mean of a quantitative variable is different among different categories. Here is the code to run one-way ANOVA:

oneway.test(log(sulphates)~quality, var.equal = FALSE, data = wine)
## 
##  One-way analysis of means (not assuming equal variances)
## 
## data:  log(sulphates) and quality
## F = 37.523, num df = 5.000, denom df = 61.832, p-value < 2.2e-16

In the one-way ANOVA, I specified var.equal = FALSE, because I concluded that the variances are not equal from Bartletts test. From the ANOVA, we get a very small p-value (certainly less than 0.05); thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean of log(sulphates) is the same across the quality groups, thereby concluding that they are different.

#run KS test

We see that the p-value is 0.6893; thus, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that these two samples have the same distribution, thereby implicitly concluding that the distribution of log(sulphates) is the same for quality = 3 wine and quality = 5 wine.   1. (8 points) Now lets visualize what the KS test in Part E is doing. The following code does this for you:
plot(ecdf(quality3wine$sulphates), pch = NA, main = "Empirical CDF", xlab = "Sulphates")

Recreate this plot for the sulphates variable instead of the log-transformed sulphates variableto do this, just appropriately change the above code. Then, using that plot, answer the following questions:

  • After you change the plot from log(sulphates) to sulphates, you should see that the x-axis changes, but the shapes of the black and red curves stay exactly the same (meaning that the KS test gives the exact same results). Why is this? Explain in 1-3 sentences.

The shape of these curves are exactly the same as the curves for log(sulphates). The reason is that, as we discussed in class, each step in the empirical CDF increases whenever there is a new unique value of log(sulphates) as we go from left to right (i.e., as we go from very negative values to more positive values). Since log() is a monotonic function, these increases will occur in the same relative place for sulphates and log(sulphates), because the ordering of observations from most negative to most positive will not change.

To put it another way: Let \(\hat{F}(x)\) be the empirical CDF for sulphates, and let \(\hat{F}_{\ell}(x)\) be the empirical CDF for log(sulphates). \(\hat{F}(x)\) is defined as the proportion of sulphates that are less than x; this will be equal to the proportion of log(sulphates) that are less than log(x) (again, this is because log is a monotonic function). This is why \(\hat{F}(x)\) and \(\hat{F}_{\ell}(x)\) will have the same shape, but different x-axes.

Finally, you can also see this equivalence by running the KS test for sulphates and log(sulphates); they yield the exact same results:

ks.test(quality3wine$sulphates, quality5wine$sulphates)
## Warning in ks.test(quality3wine$sulphates, quality5wine$sulphates): cannot
## compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  quality3wine$sulphates and quality5wine$sulphates
## D = 0.22717, p-value = 0.6893
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided
ks.test(log(quality3wine$sulphates), log(quality5wine$sulphates))
## Warning in ks.test(log(quality3wine$sulphates), log(quality5wine$sulphates)):
## cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  log(quality3wine$sulphates) and log(quality5wine$sulphates)
## D = 0.22717, p-value = 0.6893
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided
  • In the plot, there are a lot more red lines than black lines. Why is this? Provide some evidence from the data to support your explanation.

There are a lot more red lines than black lines in the plot because there are many more quality = 5 wines than quality = 3 wines. We can see this by looking at the number of rows for each of these subsets of the data:

nrow(quality3wine); nrow(quality5wine)
## [1] 10
## [1] 681
  • In the plot, the vertical gap between each individual red line is bigger on the left-hand side of the plot than on the right-hand side of the plot. Why is this? Provide some evidence from the data to support your explanation.

As mentioned earlier, in the empirical CDF, there will be a step for every unique value of sulphates. If there is only a single observation with that unique value, the corresponding step will increase by 1/n; however, if there are \(j\) observations with that unique value, the corresponding step will increase by \(j/n\). Thus, the fact that the steps have bigger gaps on the left-hand side of the plot suggests that there are more observations with the same sulphates value for low-valued sulphates. Indeed, by looking at a table of unique values of sulphates within quality = 5 wines, we can see that there are many observations with the same sulphates value when sulphates is small, but not when it is large:

table(quality5wine$sulphates)

Thus, when we look at the above table from lowest values to highest values, we know that the step of the red lines increases by 1/n at 0.37, but then 4/n for 0.39, and so on.

  1. (4pts) Now that youve shown Professor Pablo how to do a two-sample KS test, he decides to do another one on his own. He states the following:

I did a two-sample KS test comparing the distribution of log(sulphates) for quality = 3 and quality = 8 wines. I got a p-value of 0.0002. This makes me confused - I thought the KS test would have especially low power here, because the sample sizes for quality = 3 and quality = 8 wines are so small. So, why is the p-value from this KS test so small?

In 1-3 sentences, answer Professor Pablos question using the graph you made in Part C. You dont need to include another graph here, but be sure to mention how you used your Part C graph to answer the question being asked here.

Hint: Professor Pablo isnt trying to trick you; its true that the p-value from the KS test really is 0.0002, and that the sample sizes for quality = 3 and quality = 8 wines are very small.

It is true that the KS test will tend to have low power in this scenario, because the sample sizes for quality = 3 and quality = 8 wines are so small:

table(wine$quality)
## 
##   3   4   5   6   7   8 
##  10  53 681 638 199  18

However, looking back at our conditional density plot in Part C, we can see that the log(sulphates) distributions for quality = 3 and quality = 8 wines are quite different: In particular, the center of the former distribution is to the left of the latter, such that the distributions only somewhat overlap. Because of this substantial difference in the distributions, the KS test is able to detect this difference, despite the low statistical power.

[More generally, the power of statistical tests is not only affected by sample size, but also the size of the effect. For example, if we were to use a t-test assessing if two population means are different, we would have a lot of power if those means are quite far apart, but only a little power if those means were very close together. This is intuitive: Its easier to detect big differences than small differences, in the sense that big differences stand out more and are thus easier to see/detect. Because there are big differences in the log(sulphates) distributions for quality = 3 and quality = 8 wines, the KS test still had a fair amount of power to detect this difference, despite the small sample size.]

Problem 2: Ridgeline Plots (25 points)

In this problem we will talk about a relatively new kind of plot called a ridgeline plot, which was developed by Claus O. Wilke a few years ago. In short, ridgeline plots are overlapping density plots that look like a mountain range; they are sometimes called joy plots because of their similarity to the famous cover of the Joy Division album Unknown Pleasures. Although we havent discussed ridgeline plots in class or lab, they use the exact same smoothed-density concepts that weve discussedthis is meant to demonstrate that the things you learn in 36-315 will (hopefully) prepare you for all sorts of neat plots youll see in the data science world.

To make ridgeline plots, youll need to install the ggridges R package; do that now by running install.packages("ggridges") in your Console. Ive found that you need to restart RStudio after installing the package; so, do that, and then load the ggridges library:

library(ggridges)

If you run into any issues installing the ggridges R package, reach out to Professor Branson.

  1. (5pts) If you made your plot in Part A correctly, you should find the following:
  • The distribution of log(sulphates) given quality = 8 for low alcohol wines is distinctly bimodal.
  • The distribution of log(sulphates) given quality = 3 for high alcohol wines is distinctly bimodal.

For the first distribution (where quality = 8 and alcohol is low), how many wines belong to the left-hand mode, and how many wines belong to the right-hand mode? Similarly, for the second distribution (where quality = 3 and alcohol is high), how many wines belong to the left-hand mode, and how many wines belong to the right-hand mode? In addition to your answer to these questions, please include any code you used to arrive at your answer (and explain how you arrived at your answer).

First, lets look at the number of observations that have quality = 8 and low alcohol content:

nrow( subset(wine, quality == 8 & alcoholCat == "low") )
## [1] 2

There are only two observations, which means that there must be only one observation that belongs to each of the two modes for the quality = 8 low alcohol wine distribution. This also explains why the two modes are exactly the same height and shape.

Now lets look at the number of observations that have quality = 3 and high alcohol content:

nrow( subset(wine, quality == 3 & alcoholCat == "high") )
## [1] 4

There are four; because the right-hand mode of this distribution is about three-times the height of the other mode, we can deduce that three observations are in the right-hand mode and one observation is in the left-hand mode. To validate this, lets look at the values of log(sulphates) for these four wines:

log(subset(wine, quality == 3 & alcoholCat == "high")$sulphates)
## [1] -0.6161861 -0.7133499 -0.9162907 -0.6539265

Indeed, we can see that only one observation has a very low log(sulphates) value, and thus only one observation belongs to that left-hand mode for high-alcohol wines with quality = 3. Meanwhile, the other three observations (which have similar log(sulphates) belong to the right-hand mode of this distribution.

  1. (6pts) Looking at your plot, Professor A. Fletcher states, When we look at high-alcohol wines with quality = 4, the density seems to be much higher than the density for low-alcohol wines with quality = 4. Thus, this must mean that there are more high-alcohol wines with quality = 4 than low-alcohol wines with quality = 4.

For this part, state whether you Agree or Disagree with this statement, and explain your answer in 1-3 sentences. In your answer, be sure to explain why there is a higher density for high-alcohol wines with quality = 4 than for low-alcohol wines with quality = 4 (it could be because of sample size - which is what Professor Fletcher is saying - or it could be because of something else).

First, we can quickly check whether or not there are actually more high-alcohol wines with quality = 4 than low-alcohol wines with quality = 4:

#number of wines with high alcohol and quality = 4
nrow( subset(wine, quality == 4 & alcoholCat == "high") )
## [1] 25
#number of wines with low alcohol and quality = 4
nrow( subset(wine, quality == 4 & alcoholCat == "low") )
## [1] 28

There are actually more low-alcohol wines with quality = 4 than high-alcohol wines with quality = 4; so, we Disagree with the statement. When looking at conditional smoothed densities, its important to remember that every density integrates to 1 (i.e., the total area under each smoothed density curve is 1). Thus, the density for a particular subgroup is relative only to that subgroup, not the entire dataset. Thus, the reason that there is a higher density of high-alcohol wines with quality = 4 compared to low-alcohol wines with quality = 4 must be because there is a relatively higher concentration of wines with similar log(sulphates) values for high-alcohol wines. We can validate this by looking at summary statistics of log(sulphates) for these two types of wines:

#summary stats for log(sulphates) for high alcohol and quality = 4
summary( log(subset(wine, quality == 4 & alcoholCat == "high")$sulphates) )
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -0.9943 -0.5978 -0.5621 -0.5835 -0.5108 -0.4005
#summary stats for log(sulphates) for low alcohol and quality = 4
summary( log(subset(wine, quality == 4 & alcoholCat == "low")$sulphates) )
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -1.1087 -0.7340 -0.6444 -0.5438 -0.5067  0.6931

Looking at the summary statistics for high-alcohol wines, we can see that log(sulphates) has a smaller range and smaller spread (as measured by IQR); in other words, there is a higher relative concentration of wines with similar log(sulphates) values for high-alcohol wines, thereby leading to a higher density (even though there isnt a big difference in sample size, compared to low-alcohol wines).

  1. (4pts) As youve (hopefully) seen in this question, it can be helpful to include information about sample size in smoothed density plots. To do this, copy-and-paste your code from Part A, and add a rug to your plot. For this part, you only need to include the desired smoothed density plot from Part A, but with a rug added. (Hint: If you cant remember how to add a rug to a plot, revisit Lab04.)
